        <section>
            <title>The Standard Deviation Rule for Normal Random Variables</title>
            <body>
                <p>We began to get a feel for normal distributions in the
                    E<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093139-0500"?>xploratory
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>D<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093146-0500"?>ata <?oxy_insert_end?>A<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093149-0500"?>nalysis<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093307-0500"?>(EDA)
                    <?oxy_insert_end?>section, when we introduced the Standard Deviation Rule (or
                    the
                        <em>68<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093209-0500" content=" "?>-<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093211-0500" content=" "?>95<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093213-0500" content=" "?>-<?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093215-0500" content=" "?>99.7</em>
                    rule) for how values in a normally-shaped <em>sample data set</em> behave
                    relative to their mean (<m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mover accent="true">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                            </m:mrow>
                            <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                        </m:mover>
                    </m:math>) and standard deviation (s). This is the same rule that dictates how
                    the distribution of a normal <em>random variable</em> behaves relative to its
                    mean <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                    </m:math> and standard deviation <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math>. Now we use probability language and notation to
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093251-0500"?>describe<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093248-0500" content="tell about"?>
                    the random variable's behavior. For example, in the EDA
                    section<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093313-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    we would have said "68% of pregnancies in our data set fall within 1 standard
                    deviation
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093320-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?>s<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093321-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    of their mean
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093330-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?><m:math
                        overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mover accent="true">
                            <m:mrow>
                                <m:mi>x</m:mi>
                            </m:mrow>
                            <m:mo>¯</m:mo>
                        </m:mover>
                    </m:math><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093332-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>."
                    The analogous statement now would be "If X, the length of a randomly chosen
                    pregnancy, is normal with mean
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093350-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?><m:math
                        overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                    </m:math><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093351-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>
                    and standard deviation
                        <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093354-0500"?>(<?oxy_insert_end?><m:math
                        overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math><?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093357-0500"?>)<?oxy_insert_end?>,
                    then <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>6</m:mn>
                        <m:mn>8</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>P</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>-</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                    </m:math>."</p>
                <p>In general, if X is a normal random variable, then the probability is</p>
                <p>68% that X falls within 1 <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math> of <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                    </m:math> , that is, in the interval <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>±</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math>
                </p>
                <p>95% that X falls within 2 <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math> of <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                    </m:math> , that is, in the interval <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>±</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math>
                </p>
                <p>99.7% that X falls within 3 <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math> of <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                    </m:math> , that is, in the interval<m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>±</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                    </m:math>
                </p>
                <p>Using probability notation, we may
                    <?oxy_comment_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093720-0500" comment="Consider replacing mu and sigma with symbols in graphic below"?>write<?oxy_comment_end?></p>
                <p>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>6</m:mn>
                        <m:mn>8</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>P</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>-</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                    </m:math>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>9</m:mn>
                        <m:mn>5</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>P</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>-</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>2</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                    </m:math>
                </p>
                <p>
                    <m:math overflow="scroll">
                        <m:mn>0</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>9</m:mn>
                        <m:mn>9</m:mn>
                        <m:mn>7</m:mn>
                        <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>P</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>(</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>-</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>X</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>&lt;</m:mo>
                        <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>+</m:mo>
                        <m:mn>3</m:mn>
                        <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                        <m:mo>)</m:mo>
                    </m:math>
                </p>
                <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image121.gif"
                    alt="A normal bell curve with some ranges marked.
At the center (peak) of the bell curve is &mu;. The area under the bell curve between &mu;-&sigma; &lt; X
&lt; &mu;+&sigma; compromises of 0.68 of the total area under the bell curve (which is 1). The area under
the bell curve between &mu;-2&sigma; &lt; X &lt; &mu;+2&sigma; is 0.95 of the total area under the curve.
Capturing even more area under the bell curve is the range of &mu;-3&sigma; &lt; X &lt; &mu;+3&sigma;,
which is 0.997 of the total area under the curve."/>
                <!-- <p>Ross, is there any way to replace mu and sigma with the real symbols</p>-->
                <p> </p>
            </body>
        </section>
        <section>
            <title>Comment</title>
            <body>
                <p>Notice that the information from the rule can be interpreted from the perspective
                    of the tails of the normal curve: since .68 is the probability of being within
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093937-0500"?>1<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093936-0500" content="one"?>
                    standard deviation of the mean, (1 - .68) / 2 = .16 is the probability of being
                    further than
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093927-0500"?>1<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093926-0500" content="one"?>
                    standard deviation below the mean (or further than
                    <?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093945-0500"?>1<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093943-0500" content="one"?>
                    standard deviation above the mean). Likewise, (1 - .95) / 2 = .025 is the
                    probability of being more than 2 standard deviations below (or above) the mean;
                    (1 - .997) / 2 = .0015 is the probability of being more than 3 standard
                    deviations below
                    (<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093901-0500"?>or<?oxy_insert_end?><?oxy_delete author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T093859-0500" content="also"?>
                    above) the mean. The three figures below illustrate this.</p>
                <!--<p>Ross, It would be nice to have the following three figures side by side. not crucial.</p>-->
                <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image122.gif"
                    alt="A normal bell curve, in which &mu;, &mu;-&sigma;,
and &mu;+&sigma; have been marked on the horizontal axis. The probability of being within one standard
deviation of &mu;, or between &mu;-&sigma; and &mu;+&sigma;, is .68 . The probability of being below
one standard deviation from the mean is the area under the bell curve to the left of &mu;-&sigma;
which is .16 . Likewise, the probability of being further than one standard deviation above the mean is
the area under the bell curve to the right of &mu;+&sigma;, which is .16 ."/>
                <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image123.gif"
                    alt="A normal bell curve. The probability of being within
two standard deviation of &mu; is .95 . The probability of being further than two standard deviations below
the mean is the area under the bell curve to the left of &mu;-2&sigma; which is .025 . The probability of
being further than two standard deviation above the mean is the area under the bell curve to the right of
&mu;+2&sigma;, which is .025 ."/>
                <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image124.gif"
                    alt="A normal bell curve. The probability of being within
three standard deviation of &mu; is .997 . The probability of being below three standard deviations from
the mean is the area under the bell curve to the left of &mu;-3&sigma; which is .0015 . The probability of
being further than three standard deviation above the mean is the area under the bell curve to the right of
&mu;+3&sigma;, which is .0015 ."/>
                <example>

                    <p>Suppose that foot length of a randomly chosen adult male is a normal random
                        variable with mean <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mi>μ</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                            <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                        </m:math> and standard deviation <m:math overflow="scroll">
                            <m:mi>σ</m:mi>
                            <m:mo>=</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>1</m:mn>
                            <m:mo>.</m:mo>
                            <m:mn>5</m:mn>
                        </m:math>. Then the Standard Deviation Rule lets us sketch the probability
                        distribution of X as follows:</p>
                    <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image127.gif"
                        alt="A probability distribution curve in which the
horizontal axis is labeled &quot;X - Foot Length.&quot; The curve is a normal bell curve. The mean, &mu;,
is at X=11. The first standard deviation is at X=9.5 and X=12.5, with probability of .68 . The second
standard deviation is X=8 and X=14, with probability of .95 . The third standard deviation is at X=6.5
and X=15.5, with probability of .997 ."/>
                    <p><em>(a)</em> What is the probability that a randomly chosen adult male will
                        have a foot length between 8 and 14 inches?
                        .95<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T094133-0500"?>,<?oxy_insert_end?>
                        or
                        95%<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T094205-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
                    <p><em>(b)</em> An adult male is almost guaranteed (.997 probability) to have a
                        foot length between what two values? 6.5 and 15.5 inches.</p>
                    <p><em>(c)</em> The probability is only 2.5% that an adult male will have a foot
                        length greater than how many inches?
                        14<?oxy_insert_start author="mmyers" timestamp="20101122T094202-0500"?>.<?oxy_insert_end?></p>
                    <image style="block" src="../webcontent/image128.gif"
                        alt="The probability distribution curve for foot lengths.
The 2nd standard deviation boundaries from the mean have been marked at X=8 and X=14 . The probability of being
within 2 standard deviations of the mean is .95, and the probability of being above 2 standard deviations
(X &gt; 14) is .025 . The probability of being below the 2nd standard deviation (X &lt; 8) is also .025 ."/>
                    <p>Now you should try a few. (Use the figure that is just before <em>part
                            (a)</em> to help you.)</p>
                    <wb:inline idref="u3_m3_normal2_tutor1" purpose="learnbydoing"/>
